{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_canvasback_ver02/data/sn87093436/00200291451/1945090101/0124.xml":{"full_text":"8\nEDITIDBIAL PAGES of the\nTime to Stop Begging\nEnd of the war has left every participating\ncountry with its own particular reconversion\nproblems. For Great Britain the chief of these\nis to reconvert herself to her once admirable\nposition of a proud and self-reliant nation.\nIt is not good to hear out of the mouth of\nWinston Churchill. for whom. as Prime Minister.\nthe people of the United States came to hold pro\nfound respect and admiration. such expressions\nas he used recently in the House of Commons in\ncondemnation of President Truman\u2018s action end\ning wartime lend-lease.\nMr. Churchill. in his statement. declared he\ncould not believe the United States \u201cwould pro\nceed in such a rough and harsh manner as to\nhamper a faithful ally who held the fort while\ntheir own American armaments were prepared.\u201c\nPrime Minister Attlee's statement on the sub\nject. while more reserved. left no doubt that Brit\nis\u2018n officialdom does not hesitate to impute to\nPresident Truman an act of great injustice to the\nBritish government and people when he resigned\nas Santa Claus. Attlee said he should have been\nconsulted before our Chief Executive acted.\nMr. Truman knows who is likely to lose when\nwe discuss anything with British statesmen. and\nhe decided that. since lend-lease had to end some\ntime. he would end it without argument; Britain\nhad to be weaned and learn to stand once again\non her own legs. It was time for her to take her\nfirst lesson.\n8 i\nDespite any official orders of the President.\nit is not the intention of our government nor is it\nthe wish of our people to stand by and see the\nBritish go hungry: but asking and receiving help\nin the exigencies of war is likely to develop into\nthe serious and shameful disease of beggary when\nthe need no longer exists. or its demands diminish.\nAlready Britain is showing unmistakable signs of\nthe kind of moral decay which. in the individual,\nleads to mendicancy.\nThe case would be different if Britain were\n\"broke.\" True. she is deeply in debt: but so are\nwe. Right now. a good accountant could prove\nthat the United States is a bankrupt, in the sense\nthat we owe more than we are worth in realizable\nassets\nGreat Britain can be no worse off. In some\nimportant respects she is better off. The natural\nresources of her empire are intact. undepleted.\nHer oil\u2014producing areas in the Near East are safe\nin her possession. while those of Southwest Asia\nand Borneo have been restored to her largely\nas result of the victorious war America has\nwaged against Japan. Britain's tin and rubber.\nwith other vast resources. have been restored to\nher by reason of the same bitter fight in which\nshe played a brave and an important but not de\nceive part.\nIn the meantime. in acting as the \u201carsenal of\ndemocracy\" America has all but exhausted her\nlead. depleted her copper. and drained her oil to\nthe point where it is foreseeable that soon we may\nbe paying through the nose for the oil our efforts\nms swam: nmtmcnn\nServing the Scandinavian-American\nPopulation of the Great Northwest\n\ufb01iiii\ufb01fso\ufb01o\u2018x Tuu' .n 2223 nus-r AVE.\nTolvphono EL 52\u201d\nK. FINA}: (KRISON. Publisher\nEffonm. STAFF\nHarry F\u2018. Fabbe\nAndrew Bjerkeseth\nWalter H Stillman\nSubscription Rate V $1.51] Per Yur\nA pubiiu\u2018anon dwiwaytai to the mterests of the\nNorwegian Swed\u2018sn. \u201dHush. mesh and ICPlandxc\npopulation of th\u00bb Urn! Nurthwest.\nSeptember, 1945\nAlvaro C. Shoemaker\nEdwin C. Gmuvaon\nKen Turay\nand blood and treasure have been instrumental\nm saving to the British Empire.\nWith these vast resources in her undisputed\npossession. and in view of the circumstances by\nwhich they remain in her possession. it ill becomes\nBritain\u2018s officials to reproach .our government\nbecause its head suggests the time has come for\nthem to put up some cash for their meal ticket.\n8 O C\nSomewhere in almost every speech by these\nofficials. and lurking in the minds of the British\npeople. is the thought that. in standing \u201calone\"\nagainst Germany. they were unselfishly protect\ning an unprepared United States.\nFirst. did Britain stand alone. except that for\na time and in the very narrowest sense she alone\nwas engaged in actual combat with the Nazis?\nShe did not. Arms and ammunition, loans. sup\nplies of all kinds. fifty destroyers. had been\ngiven her during the time she was standing\n\u201calone.\" In a more amiable and truthful moment.\nChurchill has said this help tilted the balance in\nher favor. prevented invasion.\nSecond. did Britain stand \u201calone\u201d to shield a\ndefenseless United States? How silly! She stood\nand fought. fought desperately and valiantly, be\ncause she had to fight or die as a nation. She\nwould have had to follow precisely the same\ncourse if she hadn\u2019t had a friend on earth, and\nshe couldn't have done it successfully, even before\nwe got into the fight. without the help we gave\nher while yet we were at peace.\nBritish 5 t a t e s m e n are not increasing the\nstature of their great nation by their continual\nwhining and beggarly conduct: by behaving as\nan aged and petulant parent who. though pro\nvided with everything by a sympathetic and in\ndulgent child. yet complains that she has been\nneglected and forsaken.\nAll America hopes devoutly and sincerely that\nEngland will rediscover her self-respect. It would\nsave us money and save her soul.\n'5\u2018: it it\nSupport Price Control\nThe Office of Price Administration is making\nthe fight of its life\u2014which may well turn into\nthe fight FOR its life.\nWith war ended and manufacturers rapidly\ngetting into production of civilian goods or in\nadvanced stages of reconversion, they see noth\ning but the O.P.A. standing between them and\nthe many billions of dollars of carefully conserved\nfunds now in the hands of millions who will be\ncrowding stores and agencies for every variety\nof goods and wares and machines.\nSo these manufacturers and their distributors\nand merchandisers have given high priority to\ntheir plot to convert the O.P.A. either into a harm\nless appenage of government or, better still\nfrom their viewpoint. a dead page in our nation\u2018s\neconomic history.\nThe American people probably never will un\nderstand the prime part played by this agency in\nfighting the war on the home front, and may\nnever justly evaluate the services of its adminis\ntrator. Chester A. Bowles. his policies and his\nleadership. This is because in applying the pur\nposes of the Act. there were unavoidable irrita\ntions\u2014and. in justice but not in carping criticism.\nsome which could have been avoided.\nHowever. this much must be admitted by all\nwho care to be fair-minded: Chester Bowles and\nhis legal instrumentality have saved American\nconsumers untold billions of dollars which other\nwise today would have been nonexistent. con\nsumed in the flames of wild in\ufb02ation. And ra\ntioning has gone far toward accomplishing its\npurpose of giving everybody a break in the dis\ntribution of necessities.\n0 O O\nThe drive to vitiate or destroy CPA. is more\ndetermined than ever before because the swag\nto be obtained by manufacturers and dealers if\nTH E SCAND l NAVIAN AMERICAN\nsuccessful'in their purpose, is greater and closer\nat hand then ever before. For this reason determi\nnation of consumers to see that price control is\nretained should be greater than ever before.\nHere is an example of what may be expected if\na firm policy is not settled upon and enforced\nat once: A great manufacturing company already\nis turning out thousands of washing machines\nweekly. But it is not placing them in the hands of\ndistributors for ultimate sale to and use by con\nsumers. It is storing them in the confident hope\nthat pressure exerted by it and other big pro\nducers will draw the teeth of O.P.A. or bring\nabout its death. These manufacturers are able\nto produce, then withhold goods in storage until\nthey are assured unreasonable prices because\nthey have vast reserves of capital accumulated\nout of swollen war profits. plus a tax refund of\nnearly six billion dollars voted them by Congress\nin its last days before adjournment.\nThese accumulations they now propose to use\nin their palpably clear plan to. take the Amer\nican consumer by the pockets and squeeze his\nsavings into their treasuries by the process of\nuncontrolled and unwarranted prices.\nThe plan for price plunder has implications far\nexceeding its effect on the individual buyer. lf\nmanufacturers, jobbers and retailers are per\nmitted to carry it into effect, prices will be jacked\nup to the point at whichthe law of diminishing\nreturns will take over, sales will decrease, fac\ntories will shut down. unemployment will spread\nlike a prairie fire\u2014then de\ufb02ation, panic, economic\nruin.\nThe people of America have no more important\nbusiness right now than to see that Congress\nsupports Chester A. Bowles in his efforts to pre\nvent return to the tragic conditions of the early\nthirties which surely we have not\u2019forgotten.\n71? if? {1?\nTheir Power Was There\nThe end of the war finds the Pacific North\nwest ready to take its place as an industrial em\npire. Demand for ships and plans with which to\nwage war vastly stimulated the activities of ex\nisting plants which had their origin in manu\nfacturing materials and products required in\npeaceful pursuits: but even more important to\nthe region\u2018s future. new industries were brought\nmagically into being to serve the insatiable ap\npetite of war.\nThroughout the region. Scandinavian names\nwere significantly numerous on the payrolls of\nwar plants. Shipyards and airplane plants and\nauxiliary manufacturing establishments\u2014in all\nof these. Scandinavians provided their full quotas\nof brains and muscle. initiative and enterprise.\nmanagement and labor.\nIn the pressure of war production. it was easy\nto forget that these names were brought to the\nPacific Northwest in many cases by pioneers who\ncame as immigrants to the Puget Sound and C0-\nlumbia wilderness. went out upon the sea. struck\ninto the deep forests. populated early villages. tn\ncarve out the civilization which surrounds us at\nevery hand today.\nO I I\nOverwhelmed by the roar of furnace and ham\nmer and forge. we do not always recognize the\nquieter but more hazardous pursuits of the fish\nermen who. throughout the war. faced the peril5\nof the sea to bring back the ocean's vast and\nprecious cohtribution of food for wartime. meat\u2018\nscarce tables. In the taking. processing and dis\ntributing of fish. Scandinavians are so numerous\nas to make them preponderant in the operation\nof this great and vital enterprise. in war and in\npeace.\nThe same may be said of the lumber industry\nbased upon the great fir and pine forests of the\nregion. From pioneer days down to the present.\nlumbering has called heavily upon Scandinavian\nbrawn and ingenuity and enterprise. Never was","height":"22116","width":"14816"}}
